<DOC><DOCNO> AP890525-0231 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 0113EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-BusinessHighlights     05-25 0834</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Business Highlights,0874</SECOND><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A federal bankruptcy judge has approveddeveloper Donald Trump's agreement to buy Eastern Airlines' prizedNortheast shuttle for $365 million.   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland approved the sale inprinciple Wednesday and will hold a hearing on the matter Thursdayat 10 a.m. EDT, said a bankruptcy court clerk, who asked not to beidentified by name.   Also Wednesday, America West Airlines withdrew a higher offerfor the shuttle, the clerk said.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The dollar resumed its climb against all keycurrencies except the British pound and Swiss franc, breaking the143-yen level overseas and hitting a 1{-year high vs. the Japanesecurrency in domestic trading.   Dealers said trading was volatile here and overseas Wednesday,with the dollar starting out weak after a mixed performance Tuesdaybut ending stronger in the absence of significant central-bankintervention or signs of policy changes geared toward stabilizingexchange rates.</TEXT><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The British government raised interest rates by afull percentage point, hiking them to a four-year high in acounterattack against newly resurgent inflation that has beenworsened by a drop in the British pound.   The Bank of England signaled the change by raising its baselending rate to 14 percent on Wednesday, and major commercial banksresponded by boosting their prime lending rates one point to thatlevel.</TEXT><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Car and truck sales rose a modest 2.7 percent inmid-May from the same period last year, manufacturers reported, butanalysts noted the sales compared with a year-earlier period thatmay have been slower than usual.   During the May 11-20 period, sales of cars and light trucks madeby the eight major U.S.-based automakers rose to a rate of 39,360 aday from a pace of 38,334 during the same period last year, the carmakers said Wednesday.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Import restraints have slowed the influx offoreign steel, but the illegal trading practices that made tradeprotection necessary 4{ years ago are as prevalent as ever,American steelmakers said.   ``We are prepared to file cases against virtually all ourtrading partners'' unless steel import limits are extended underthe five-year Voluntary Restraint Agreements, Bethlehem Steel Corp.chairman Walter F. Williams told reporters Wednesday at the annualmeeting of the American Iron and Steel Institute.   President Bush is expected to fulfill a campaign promise toextend quotas past their Sept. 30 expiration. But steel executivesare concerned he may weaken the restraints.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The fuel-economy standard for 1989 passengercars will remain at 26.5 miles per gallon, the National HighwayTraffic Safety Administration said in rejecting a petition forreconsideration of the regulation.   The petition filed by two Washington-based advocacy groups, theCenter for Auto Safety and Public Citizen, asked NHTSA to allow thecorporate average fuel economy standard to revert to 27.5 mpg, thelevel set by a 1975 law intended to reduce dependence on foreignoil.   The advocacy groups failed to make a case that ``the standardshould have been set at a level other than 26.5 mpg,'' NHTSA'sorder said Wednesday.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A House subcommittee approved a bill givingthe federal government authority to determine damages to be paid byoil companies after spills.   The measure approved by the House Merchant Marine and FisheriesCoast Guard subcommittee Wednesday bars states from enactingstricter damage laws than the federal standard. The issue of stateversus federal standard has been the chief hurdle over the past 13years blocking legislation to simplify existing oil spill laws.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The House Judiciary Committee narrowlydefeated a Republican attempt to blunt the key capital reform inPresident Bush's savings and loan bailout.   The amendment, which failed on a 17-17 vote Wednesday, wouldhave allowed some institutions to use administrative appeals todelay the imposition of tougher capital standards for up to a yearand half.   That vote was the latest in a series by both the Judiciary paneland House Banking Committee in which Bush has attracted moreDemocratic than Republican support for preserving his proposedreforms.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   About 36 cents of every dollar of Americans'income goes for taxes, with the nation's poorest and wealthiestfamilies paying considerably more than average, the Tax Foundationreported.   In 1986, households under $10,000 gave just about half theirincomes _ 49.5 percent _ to federal, state and local governments.Those with incomes of $90,000 and more paid an average 51.6percent, the foundation said Wednesday.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The stock market shook off an early slump and closed higherWednesday in a generally quiet session. The Dow Jones average of 30industrials closed up 5.86 points at 2,483.87.   The dollar advanced against all major currencies except theBritish pound.   Bond prices edged lower on technical factors.   Energy futures prices climbed; grain and soybean prices driftedlower, precious metals finished mixed, and livestock and porkprices plunged.</TEXT></DOC>